    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Optimization of Sustained Release</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Mothilal.M</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">OPTIMIZATION OF SUSTAINED RELEASE<br />OPTIMIZATION OF SUSTAINED RELEASE</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Jan-2012 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0055</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">ABSTRACT
Diltiazem hydrochloride is a calcium channel blocker, used widely
for the treatment of hypertension, atrial fibrillation and angina pectoris. The
drug is water soluble and has elimination half life of 3.0 to 4.5 h. It is reported
to be well absorbed in the proximal region of small intestine and so it is an
ideal candidate for gastro-retentive systems, which supplies a constant amount
of drug for absorption continuously from the dosage form to the proximal
region of small intestine, where it is well absorbed, leading to more uniform
plasma levels of the drug for prolonged period and thereby paves way for an
efficient drug therapy in treatment of angina pectoris. The present study is an
endeavour to develop a perfect sustained release formulation for Diltiazem
hydrochloride. The study was aimed to identify a bilayer floating tablet
formulation of Diltiazem hydrochloride with one immediate release layer and
another sustained release floating layer, which release the drug for 12 h. Two
viscosity grades of hydroxypropyl methyl cellulose (HPMC K4M and K15M)
and crosspovidone were used to prepare Diltiazem hydrochloride bilayer
floating tablets (BFT).
A numerical optimization technique was adapted, which are designed
based on 23 full factorial design containing three factors evaluated at two
levels and the experimental trials were performed at all possible
combinations. Eight runs were carried out for formulations with HPMC K4M
and another eight for HPMC K15M formulations totally sixteen runs were
done and evaluated for the in vitro drug release and in vitro buoyancy
characteristics.
viii
Independent variables studied were, the drug : total polymer ratio
(X1), Sodium carboxy methyl cellulose (SCMC) : Hydroxy propyl methyl
cellulose (HPMC) ratio (X2) and gas generating agent, Sodium bicarbonate
content (X3). In case of HPMC K4M the dependent variables studied were,
cumulative percentage release of drug after 12 hours (Y1), time to release 50%
of drug (Y2), burst release of the tablets (Y3) and floating lag time (Y4). In
case of HPMC K15M the dependant variables studied were burst release (Y1),
drug release at 12 h (Y2), drug release at 3 h (Y3). The optimized BFT
formulations HFAO1 containing HPMC K4M and HFBO1 containing HPMC
K15M were identified with the help of DesignExpert software ver.7.1.0 they
were prepared and evaluated for the responses. The actual response values
were in accordance with the predicted values.
Drug release best fit both the Higuchi model and the Korsmeyer and
Peppas model. The diffusion coefficient (n) for HFAO1 and HFBO1 were
0.729 and 0.876 respectively. The mechanism of drug release followed a non
fickian anamolous transport, the release was controlled both by diffusion and
swelling. The drug release profile of optimized formulations when compared
to markedly available conventional sustained release tablets, release of
Diltiazem hydrochloride from these BFT systems was showing an burst
release followed with a sustained release. The 23 full factorial design had
facilitated the study to identify optimum formulation and to understand the
influence of different factors and interactions between them on the key
characteristics of the sustained release floating dosage form</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/6871">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/6871</a></td></tr>
